{"key":"processedPost-13147280","value":{"id":13147280,"first":13147241,"last":13148675,"when":1283634445,"utime":"09/05/10 12:07 AM","content":"Actually, they do matter.&nbsp; Normally, they're caused by a temperature differential where the substrate is warmer than the surrounding air.&nbsp; They're compounded by a lack of air exchange, which prevents them from evaporating.<br />They can also be caused by 'incubating' which stimulates bacteria, thus more metabolites than normal are on the surface.&nbsp; Whatever the cause, more fresh air on the substrate is the answer.<br />If they're really bad, take the corner of a paper towel and dab them up.&nbsp; They won't cause aborts, but if they're metabolites, they can mess with your substrate pH, so it's best to get rid of them.<br />RR","title":"Re: Lots of water on surface of sub in monotub?"}}